Exploring Health Data with KNN¶

Complete by: Tuesday 18 Mar. at class time
Data: https://jrladd.com/CIS241/data/500_Cities_small.csv

What does it mean for a place to be healthy? What can we learn about the overall health of people in the United States by looking at health by city and locality? These are the questions that the CDC's PLACES project attempts to answer. This project originally began in 2015 as the "500 Cities Project": an annual survey of the 500 largest cities in the US. By surveying these cities every year, the CDC hopes to better understand long-term health among Americans all across the country.

As we continue through the COVID-19 pandemic, data analysis focused on health and healthcare continues to be at the center of public conversation. Good data analysis in this domain is essential for public health in the 21st century. In this week's workshop, you'll examine recent data from the PLACES project to better understand American's overall health.

As you go through each section, make sure you are explaining, describing and interpreting all code, visualizations, and statistical output. The goal is that a reader with no previous knowledge of the data should be able to understand your findings.*

KNN Regression¶

Physical Health means that individuals have the ability to function properly, engage in physical activity, and maintain a healthy lifestyle, ultimately promoting overall health and preventing disease.

Bias refers to the difference between the model's average prediction and the true value. A high bias means the model makes bad assumptions and might miss important relationships in the data, leading to oversmoothing. Variance measures how much the model's predictions vary for different training datasets. High variance means the model is too sensitive to the training data and might overfit, capturing noise instead of underlying patterns. A lower k-value would have too much variance, skewing the data, whereas a higher k-value would cause too much bias, leading to invalid conclusions. After trying several different values for k, I chose 7.

In [6]:
target = ["Physical Health"]
predictors = ["Obesity", "Cancer (except skin)", "COPD", "Mental Health", "Health Insurance"]

First, I chose the predictor variables, which were Obesity, Cancer (except skin), COPD, Mental Health, and Health Insurance. After that, I split the data into training and testing portions using the test_train_split function. After splitting the data, I scaled the values of my predictor variables in my training data to prevent variables with higher weights from affecting the results.

In [7]:
cities = cities.dropna()
X = pd.get_dummies(cities[predictors])
y = cities[target]

# Split data BEFORE standardizing
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, 
    y, 
    test_size=0.4, 
    random_state=42)

# Standardizing using the training data
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)
X_train_std = scaler.transform(X_train)

I then fit the KNN regressor using the standardized training data for both my predictor and target variables, using 7 as the value for k for the reasons noted above. Next, I standardized the values of my predictor variables in my test data for the same reasons as to why I standardized the predictor variable values for my training data.

In [8]:
# Fit the KNN Regressor
knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=7)
knn.fit(X_train_std, y_train)

# Standardize test data before predicting!
X_test_std = scaler.transform(X_test)
predictions = knn.predict(X_test_std)

KNN Classification¶

In order to find states with more than 40 cities, I would need to perform the following data wrangling steps"

In [25]:
twoStates = [] # Create an empty list that plans to have 2 elements
states = cities.StateAbbr.unique() # Create a list of unique states
for i in range(len(states)):
    if (len(cities.loc[cities["StateAbbr"] == states[i]])) > 40:
        twoStates.append(states[i])

twoStatesDF = cities[(cities["StateAbbr"] == twoStates[0]) | (cities["StateAbbr"] == twoStates[1])]

First, I created an empty list so that I can append the two states with more than 40 cities later on. After that, I created a list of all the states included in the original dataframe, making sure that no states were duplicated. I did this using the .unique() method. Then, I created a loop that iterates through each individual state in order to determine if the state had more than 40 cities. If a state had more than 40 citites, it would be appended to the twoStates list. After running these steps, only two states had more than 40 cities. These were California and Texas. After determining the two cities with more than 40 states, I created a subset of the cities DataFrame, making sure that the only states included were California and Texas.

I chose 5 as the value for k because there is very little data to work with. If I chose anything higher, the model would underfit the data, causing bias. Conversely, If I chose anything lower, the model would overfit the data, causing variance. I also standardized the test data for the same reasons as to why I standardized the training data, which is that variables with higher weights might skew the data.

conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test2,predictions2)

    x=alt.X("variable:N").title("Predicted Response"),

)

    size=alt.value(50)
)

Alternatively, the model incorrectly assumed predicted 1 sample to be located in Texas, when in reality it was located in California, and 11 times it correctly assumed that the health related issues were located in Texas.
